      "text": "The boy leads Theo to a modest courtyard school where an old Greek tutor — a freed slave named Diodorus — is explaining Roman economics to a handful of students.\n\n'Conquest created Rome's wealth,' Diodorus says, scratching numbers into a wax tablet. 'But that wealth flows upward. When Rome conquers a province, the generals and senators seize the land. They bring back thousands of war captives as slaves. Perhaps one-third of Italy's population is now enslaved.'\n\nHe draws a circle. 'Here is the problem: the small farmer was the backbone of the legions. He fought because he had land to defend. Now the land belongs to senators who work it with slaves. The farmer has nothing. So he drifts to Rome, joins the urban poor, and waits for someone to feed him.'\n\n'And the senators?' a student asks.\n\n'The senators feed him,' Diodorus says drily. '**Panem et circenses** — bread and circuses. Free grain from the **annona**, gladiator shows at the arena. Feed a man and entertain him, and he won't burn down your villa. It's cheaper than justice.'",
