      "text": "Theo spends days in a cramped room above a bakery, copying the land reform bill onto scroll after scroll. The bill is simple: no Roman may hold more than 500 **iugera** of **ager publicus**. The surplus goes back to landless citizens in small allotments.\n\nIt seems fair. It is, technically, already the law — an old law that the Senate has simply refused to enforce for decades.\n\nWhen the day of the vote arrives, the **popular assembly** is packed. But as Tiberius rises to speak, another tribune — Octavius, bought by the Senate — stands and shouts: '*Veto!*' A single word that, by ancient law, can stop any action.\n\nTiberius does something unprecedented: he asks the assembly to vote Octavius out of office. The crowd roars approval. Octavius is dragged from the platform. The land bill passes.\n\nBut the scribe beside Theo has gone pale. 'He's won the battle,' the scribe whispers. 'But he's just shown Rome that a tribune can remove another tribune by force of the mob. What happens when someone less honorable uses that trick?'",
