      "title": "The Invisible People",
      "text": "A slave named Philo — Greek-born, taken prisoner in a war he never asked for — tells Theo what life is really like at the bottom of Rome's pyramid.\n\n'We build the roads. We harvest the grain. We teach the senators' children to read Greek. We copy their manuscripts, run their businesses, row their warships. Perhaps one-third of Italy is enslaved.'\n\n'And the revolts?' Theo asks, remembering something from a history class that feels like a dream.\n\nPhilo glances around nervously. '**Spartacus**. Forty years from now, a gladiator will lead seventy thousand slaves against Rome. He will terrify the masters. And he will lose.' Philo's voice drops. 'But the fear he creates — that never goes away.'\n\nA foreman's whip cracks. Philo flinches back to work. Theo stands in the Roman sun, understanding for the first time that this magnificent civilization is built on human suffering.",
