      "text": "After the speech, Theo manages to push through Tiberius's circle of friends. The tribune is younger than Theo expected — barely thirty, with shadows under his eyes.\n\n'You want to know if it will work?' Tiberius says, reading Theo's face. 'The truth? I don't know. The law is on our side. Justice is on our side. But the men who own the **latifundia** also own the Senate, and they will not give up their stolen land because a tribune asks politely.'\n\n'Then why try?'\n\nTiberius looks out over the Forum. 'Because the men who fought Rome's wars deserve to come home to something. Because a republic that exists only for the rich is already dead — it just doesn't know it yet.'\n\nHe grips Theo's arm. 'Stay close. Whatever happens next, I want someone to remember it clearly.'",
